<li id="cite_note-33"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-33">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFStanovich2007">Stanovich 2007</a> pg 119–138</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-34"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-34">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a href="#CITEREFStanovich2007">Stanovich 2007</a> pg 123</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-35"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-35">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation book"><a href="/wiki/Ludwik_Fleck" title="Ludwik Fleck">Fleck, Ludwik</a> (1979). Trenn, Thaddeus J.; Merton, Robert K. eds. <i>Genesis and Development of a Scientific Fact</i>. Chicago: University of Chicago Press. <a href="/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number" title="International Standard Book Number">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-226-25325-2" title="Special:BookSources/0-226-25325-2">0-226-25325-2</a>.</span> Claims that before a specific fact "existed", it had to be created as part of a social agreement within a community. <a href="/wiki/Steven_Shapin" title="Steven Shapin">Steven Shapin</a> (1980) "A view of scientific thought" <i>Science</i> ccvii (7 Mar 1980) 1065-66 states "[To Fleck,] facts are invented, not discovered. Moreover, the appearance of scientific facts as discovered things is itself a social construction: a <i>made</i> thing. "</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-36"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-36">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation news">Dawkins, Richard; Coyne, Jerry (2005-09-02). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2005/sep/01/schools.research">"One side can be wrong"</a>. <i>The Guardian</i> (London)<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2005/sep/01/schools.research">http://www.guardian.co.uk/science/2005/sep/01/schools.research</a></span>.</span></span></li>
