<li id="cite_note-44"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-44">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><cite id="COPE1999PDF"><span class="citation Journal"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://web.archive.org/web/20070928151119/http://www.publicationethics.org.uk/reports/1999/1999pdf3.pdf">"Coping with fraud"</a> (PDF). <i>The COPE Report 1999</i>: 11–18. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.publicationethics.org.uk/reports/1999/1999pdf3.pdf">the original</a> on 2007-09-28<span class="printonly">. <a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://web.archive.org/web/20070928151119/http://www.publicationethics.org.uk/reports/1999/1999pdf3.pdf">http://web.archive.org/web/20070928151119/http://www.publicationethics.org.uk/reports/1999/1999pdf3.pdf</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 2011-07-21</span>. "It is 10 years, to the month, since Stephen Lock ... Reproduced with kind permission of the Editor, The Lancet."</span></cite></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-45"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-45">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">In mathematics, <a href="/wiki/Plato" title="Plato">Plato</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Meno#Dialogue_with_Meno.27s_slave" title="Meno">Meno</a></i> demonstrates that it is possible to know logical propositions, such as the <a href="/wiki/Pythagorean_theorem" title="Pythagorean theorem">Pythagorean theorem</a>, and even to prove them, as cited by <a href="#CITEREFCrease2009">Crease 2009</a>, pp.&#160;35–41</span></li>
